Doctor '''Charles Maitland''' (1668–1748) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] surgeon who [[inoculation|inoculated]] people against [[smallpox]]. 

==Career==
He [[inoculation|inoculated]] two of [[Lady Mary Wortley Montagu]]'s children during a [[smallpox]] epidemic: her five-year-old son in March 1718 in [[Constantinople]], Turkey, and her daughter, who was four, in April 1721 in [[London]],<ref name="riedel">{{cite journal | title=Edward Jenner and the history of smallpox and vaccination | journal=Proceedings ([[Baylor University]] Medical Center) | year=2005 | month=January | last=Riedel | first=Stefan | pmc=1200696 | pmid=16200144 | volume=18 | issue=1 | pages=21–5}}</ref> which was the first professional inoculation in England.<ref name="giblin">{{cite book | title=When Plague Strikes: The Black Death, Smallpox, AIDS | publisher=[[HarperCollins]] | year=1995 | location=[[New York City|New York]] | page=80 | isbn=0-0-025854-3 | last=Giblin | first=James Cross | url=http://books.google.com/books?id=owTYomOHNbsC}}</ref> The family promoted inoculation in England.<ref name="henderson">{{cite book |title= Smallpox: The Death of a Disease: the Inside Story of Eradicating a Worldwide Killer |last=Henderson |first=D. A. |authorlink=Donald Henderson |year=2009 |publisher=[[Prometheus Books]] |location=[[Amherst, New York|Amherst]] |isbn=978-1-59102-722-5 |page=45 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=g3TYOwAACAAJ |accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref>

On 9 August 1721, Maitland received a Royal License that allowed him to test variolation on six prisoners in [[Newgate Prison]].<ref name="riedel"/><ref name="persson">{{cite book | title=Smallpox, Syphilis and Salvation: Medical Breakthroughs That Changed the World | publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com | year=2010 | isbn=9781458767127 | url=http://books.google.com/books?id=-W7ch1d6JOoC | last=Persson | first=Sheryl | page=16}}</ref> The experiment took place in August 1722, under the direction of Sir [[Hans Sloane]].<ref name="lecture">{{cite book | title=The History of Inoculation and Vaccination for the Prevention and Treatment of Disease | publisher=[[GlaxoSmithKline|Burroughs Wellcome And Company]] | author=Lecture memoranda | year=1913 | location=London | pages=44–45 | isbn=9781152540699 | url=http://www.archive.org/stream/historyofinocula00burrrich#page/n9/mode/2up}}</ref> All prisoners survived, and one who was exposed to the disease proved to be immune.<ref name="persson"/> They were [[pardon]]ed later that year.<ref name="cunningham">{{cite book | title=The Medical Enlightenment of the Eighteenth Century | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] | year=1990 | location=[[New York City|New York]] | isbn=0-521-825-1 | last=Cunningham | first=Andrew | url=http://books.google.com/books?id=djHCBZQINrgC | page=27}}</ref>

In late 1722, [[Caroline of Ansbach]] ordered the inoculation of five orphans of St. James's Parish in [[London]]. Following their success, Caroline had Maitland inoculate her eldest son, [[Frederick, Prince of Wales|Frederick]] and one other child.<ref name="lecture"/><ref name="van der kiste">{{cite book | title=George II and Queen Caroline | publisher=[[The History Press|Sutton Publishing]] | authorlink=John Van der Kiste | year=1997 | location=Stroud, Gloucestershire | page=83 | isbn=0-7509-1321-5 | last=Van der Kiste | first=John | url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ehR2AAAAIAAJ}}</ref>

The surgeon died in [[Aberdeen]], Scotland in 1748.<ref name="carrell">{{cite book | title=The Speckled Monster: A Historical Tale of Battling Smallpox | url=http://books.google.com/books?id=4UjMbmROq8IC | publisher=[[Penguin Books]] | authorlink=Jennifer Lee Carrell | year=2004 | location=[[New York City]] | isbn=978-0452285071 | last=Carrell | first=Jennifer Lee}}</ref>

